instream media abandoned labor in favor of consumer and business interests. When newspapers, especially, wrote off working-class readers as useless for their business model, the American worker became invisible. In No Longer Newsworthy, Martin covers this shift in focus, the loss of political voice for the working class, and the emergence of a more conservative media in the form of Christian television, talk radio, Fox News, and conservative websites.Now, with our fractured society and news media, Martin offers the mainstream media recommendations for how to push back against right-wing media and once again embrace the working class as critical to its audience and its democratic function.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aIndustrial relationsxPress coveragezUnited States. 0aJournalismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aJournalismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aLabor unions and mass mediazUnited States. 0aWorking classxPress coveragezUnited States. 4aCurrent Events. 4aLabor History. 4aMedia Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aAmerican working class, mainstream media, labor, conservative media, labor unions, consumer and business interests.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501735264?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501735264423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501735264/original  a978-3-11-065198-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles